The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New York, May 4: Investors dumped US stocks as fears grew that the financial rescue package for Greece might not be enough to prevent a sovereign debt crisis from spreading to other weak euro zone countries. Wall Streets major indices slid more than 2 per cent, while European shares dipped 3 per cent. Commodities sank and the euro hit a one-year low against the dollar.                            
	 New Delhi, May 4: Indias annual exports for 2009-10 may show a single-digit percentage shortfall compared with 2008-09, commerce minister Anand Sharma said. Exports in 2008-09 were worth $185 billion. Data for 2009-10 is likely to be released later this week.                            
	 Mumbai, May 4: Larsen amp; Toubro (L amp;T) has signed a joint venture agreement with UK-based Howden to design, engineer, manufacture and supply axial fans and air pre-heaters to Indian thermal power plants with capacities ranging between 100mw and 1,200mw                             
	 New Delhi, May 4: Foreign direct investment dipped 5.16 per cent to $25.89 billion in 2009-10, which analysts said was good given the global credit squeeze. FDI inflows in 2008-09 stood at $27.30 billion. In March, the inflows fell 38 per cent to $1.21 billion from $1.95 billion a year ago.                            
	 London, May 4: Essar Energy today listed its shares on the London Stock Exchange after its 1.2-billion IPO. The shares of the company were trading at 398.25 pence in the afternoon session on the LSE after touching the days high of 419.62 pence.                            
	 New Delhi, May 4: Parliament today passed the budget for 2010-11, keeping the hike in duties on fuels intact as finance minister Pranab Mukherjee said the present fiscal situation did not permit a rollback.                            
	 Mumbai, May 4: Sebi has permitted bourses to introduce index options contracts on the sensex and the Nifty for five years against the three-year tenure set earlier.
                                                                                                                          
